n, the dominant techno-economic paradigm of our time. By centering the spatiality of digital capitalism, Alvarez Leon shows how this system is the product not of seemingly intangible information clouds but rather of a vast array of technologies, practices, and infrastructures deeply rooted in place, mediated by geography, and open to contestation and change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMobile geographic information systemsxEconomic aspects. 0aMobile geographic information systems. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Computers & Information Technology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520389335?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520389335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520389335/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles